review_data.review_title: Still very good but service off
review_data.review: We eat here once or twice a year during our annual stay in Paris and it is one of our favorites. Service this year felt remarkably different. In the past we always received a gluten-free menu for my celiac husband without asking (I specify in my booking that he needs a gluten-free meal). This year we had to ask for it. I ordered a cocktail and my husband an aperitif. Before we even received them, the waiter asked if we wanted to order our meal. I don't think I have ever had that happen in a Michelin-starred restaurant. It felt like dining in a cafe. We said we would prefer to have our drinks and then order. In prior years we always looked forward to the mignardise at the end of the meal. They would always tell my husband which things he could have and fill in with macarons if too many of the usual mignardise had gluten. This time we noticed we were the only table that didn't receive any. We asked the waiter and he said that my husband would not be able to eat them (not true - they included macarons). I asked why did I not get any. He said he assumed that I would not want any if my husband could not have any. That's like saying I would not eat bread at a meal if he couldn't have any. We asked for a manager and he apologized and we got our mignardise. I gave my husband ones that I knew were OK for him and they obviously were since he had no effect from them. The manager gave us his card and assured us that next time he would make sure we were properly taken care of. These are small things, and the cocktail and food and wine were excellent, but we have been here quite a number of times before and the the service was flawless and friendly in the past to the point where a waiter we had on an earlier visit would come over and say hello. Also, it does have a Michelin star and you should not have to worry about anything in such a restaurant. Hopefully this is an isolated incident and does not reflect their normal service.

Restaurant is housed in a period building in a Picturesque London street. It is a warren of small cozy rooms but you don’t feel hemmed in or claustrophobic. Modern decor with lots of natural light.  Had a la carte of veal cheek and lobster to start , extremely tasty and beautifully presented. Not the biggest portions, but they do start you off with amuse buche and some delightful warm bread. Cheese trolley followed with a good mix of British and continental. These were very well described and waiters seemed knowledgeable on the flavours and the provenance.  A chocolate delight was then shared to round off an excellent afternoon.  Service was tremendous throughout, attentive but not overbearing with humour and personality.  Look forward to returning. I am sure it will be no time at all before they regain their star.

review_data.review_title: Two restaurants for the price of one!
review_data.review: The Sohhhak River is actually two restaurants, both of which have the same Khmer menu. The one next door is called the Charnery Tree and only serves the Khmer version. Sokkhak River, however, also has a French Fusion menu as well as tables inside with air conditioning, whereas Chanery Tree only has tables outside. As it wax another hot day in Siem Reap I opted to eat insid.  The French menu is really a Western menu offering mostly steaks, seafood and pasta main dishes for around $20-25. The Khmer menu is about half that price and looked much more interesting offering local classics like Amok, Lok Lak as well as the temptingly exotic Grilled Stuffed Frog, but as I was feeling less adventurous I opted for the Tonle Sap Steamed Fish ($11.50); Bar fish fillet with garlic, shallot, basil, spring onion, cashew and lime dressing. To drink with lunch I ordered a glass of the Obikwa Chardonnay from South Africa. Like all the red and white wines by the glass this cost $5.80.  The Chardy was nice - quite a lot of body with pear flavours. An easy drinking cheap and cheerful! The Sokkhak is very comfortable and stylish. There are two red and black display cases filled with small potted tropical plants, statues and other knick knacks that subtly divide the space in two, black tiled floors, contemporary local art on the walls, and dark wood sideboards where the settings are kept. I had a table near one of the windows that looked out onto a narrow breezeway filled with ferns that separated the restaurant from its sister property next door.  My main was delivered quickly and was very good. The fish was tasty and soft, and the sauce tart and flavoursome but not so much as to over power the main ingredient. The cashews added a nice crunch to an otherwise soft-mouthed dish. I think I did a good job matching the wine too as this complemented the dish very well.  I'd had the tasting menu at another high end restart just next door called Malis a couple of nights before which I really liked, but a couple of locals said this place was better. Personally I liked them both, but it's hard to compare the diverse tastes and experience of a degustation against a single dish. However based on the one I tried here today I'd have to call it a tie. I'd really like Chanery Tree/Sokkhak to introduce a tasting plate to their menu as there were a lot of things they do that I'd really like to try - starting, of course, with the stuffed frog

Whilst at the resort we made a number of visits to the Sala Sawasdee bar. It’s a great place to relax and have a drink, regardless if you’re a hotel guest or visiting from the outside.  Something that really makes the place special is the staff and the stand out for my family was Mai Butsaba. It has been over a year since our last visit and Mai instantly recognised my family and particularly my daughters. She went out of her way to make us feel welcome on every visit. Thank you Mai.  It’s a great spot to sit and have a cocktail on the evening when the fire show is on, just get there early to make sure you get a water side day bed.  Thanks Sala Sawasdee team and especially Mai, we have a wonderful visit and look forward to seeing you all again soon.

review_data.review_title: Excellent! Magazine Worthy! Amazing! Bravo! Brilliant!
review_data.review: We had the best meal (gluten-free as well) in Siem Reap at Haven! The food was absolutely superb and the concept--training the locals to help themselves--is brilliant. The service was perfect and the food, oh my stars, the food! Magnificent!  If you're wondering where to dine while in Siem Reap, look no further and secure your reservation as soon as possible. We were so fortunate to have secured a table. Seriously, we speak so highly of this restaurant, even compared to the Embassy.  We had the fresh spring rolls and the pomelo salad, the outstanding beef loc lac, fish soup, and chicken Khmer curry. We had three traditional Cambodian desserts. The loc lac was amazing! Amazing! The Khmer curry was the absolute best of all the places we dined at in Siem Reap. Honestly and truthfully, so amazing. As a matter of fact, while we were fine dining at the Embassy, we were contemplating heading over to Haven after to scoop up a heartier meal. The desserts were delicious and like written online, were not sweet, swimming in coconut milk, and served hot. Everything was a winner and the chef was able to make the fried calamari gluten-free as well.  Danke Schoen for the best meal. So looking forward to dining at Haven on our next visit.  Notes: al fresco dining and not a mosquito in sight.  $65 USD

review_data.review_title: Great experience at a reasonable price
review_data.review: We made a reservation at Aspic solely based on the glowing reviews on Trip Advisor and we were not disappointed.  As others have mentioned this is a fixed menu only type of restaurants so you need to be flexible but what came out of the kitchen on the night we were there did not disappoint one bit. What was interesting is that unlike many of the other restaurants we went to during our trip to France, Aspic offered a wine pairing with the meal which was quite nice and added an extra layer to the experience.  Service was overall good but you need to go into this with the right expectation that this is a lean operation. As far as I could tell there was the chef in the kitchen and one waitress for about 12 tables. It didn't feel slow or anything but it wasn't "high touch" either.  Overall we were pleasantly surprised with the experience. When the check came in, we were even more surprised at how affordable this experience was. Given the quality and creativity, I don't think it's going to stay this way for long so you better go and enjoy it!

We decided to try something different on our last trip to New York and opted for Jungsik. We opted for the signature tasting with premium wines and we were not disappointed! Each course was flavorful with premium ingredient and original presentation. Service was friendly, attentive and efficient. The wine pairing although expensive really helped bring an additional dimension to the food with the sommelier walking us through each pairing in details.  Overall we had a wonderful night at Jungsik and even though it's not as well known as some of the other high-end restaurants in New York, we highly recommend you give it a shot!

This was a truly special meal. When coming to restaurant of this type, I would highly suggest just going with it. Take the meal as the chef intends the experience to be and make sure to absolutely add the wine pairings. The flavors of the perfectly chosen wines are essential to the full experience and appreciation of the complex flavors. We have had meals of this type several times but this was definitely one of the best. The intricacy of the preparation to pair multiple different types of ingredients (sometimes ones you would not think would go together) to get a specific flavor or texture is truly amazing. I can’t really cook much of anything so this of course is even more special for me – as I LOVE to eat great food. Only 20 seats in this compact and quaint place so make sure you book well in advance if you want this experience. The staff was wonderful and the evening was perfect – especially since it was our 25th anniversary.

In warm weather there is outside dining in the shadow of the Charles Bridge. Here are the items we really liked: scallops, celery cream soup, goat cheese salad, filet schnitzel (sounds odd but great) and cream puff. Full bar with all the usual mixed drinks. Very pleasant setting with just enough ambient noise to allow a normal conversation. Reservation needed if you want a preferential seating location.

The concept is that you can chose from a choice of fish and meats, chose your style and combine the two. The tasting platter is put together by the chef. We especially liked the Tuna Niçoise, a mix we otherwise wouldn't have tried! Definitely recommend that, the Italian veal (like a carpaccio) and the beef house-style. The Poké Salmon was also good, but obviously similar to a normal salmon poké.  The portions of the tasting platter are rather small and we felt like some could've used a bit more spices or salt as they were quite bland. The dessert on the other hand was amazing! We had the speculoos Tiramisu and I would go back just for that dessert! Absolutely great.  Service was quick and attentive although our server seemed to be new. The owner (I assume) was great though.  There's a bus stop right in front of the restaurant.

Rice was ok....had peas in it which was odd (for an indian) but then we've experienced peas on pizza this week so not all that weird.  The poppadoms we had for starters were strange, cone shaped and quite small but they were fairly priced so not a problem, not enough indian dips with them though.  Usual selection of drinks, no problems there and the peshwari naan was very good.  Some people came in with a very large dog, don't really like dogs in restaurants but it was fairly well behaved so not a major issue.

This restaurant is so incredibly small and authentic, it will become your immediate favorite! Definitely eat here if you're craving the best Thai food in NYC!!

review_data.review_title: Excellent Meal, Excellent Service, Perfect Evening
review_data.review: We came here for dinner on the night we landed in Paris. Our flight was supposed to arrive at 8:20pm, and their last order was at 10:15pm (be aware that even though they offer 10:30pm reservations on La Fourchette, they don't actually do that), so I initially canceled because I was worried we'd miss the reservation. They were exceedingly nice and understanding during the email exchange, and so when we arrived on time and realized we could still make it, we had our hotel call them, and they were able to accommodate us.  Particularly for a late night dinner, the meal was better than I could have expected. The servers were kind and didn't rush us at all even though we ordered the chef's menu. Particularly memorable was the artichoke soup which was divine, the best I'd ever had with bits of artichoke mixed in with the velvety smooth soup. My husband, who is usually a non-meat eater, said the lamb was one of the best he had tasted. If you come here, you must have the bread, even if you are trying to cut down on carbs. It's absolutely delicious. On this night, we had something that looked like parker rolls, but actually tasted like a nice focaccia, and a perfectly baked sourdough slice.  If you are a dessert lover like me, you will love the long list of some of the most scrumptious choices I've seen at a restaurant in a long time. The menu came with a caramel mille-feuille, which I enjoyed, but I also saw tantalizing plates of soufflés, berry tarts etc etc making its way toward other tables. I would love to come and just eat all of their desserts.  The restaurant was located inside the Bristol hotel, which is a former palace. The warm and unpretentious service combined with the amazing food even made me curious about staying here next time.  Pricewise, this is a one Michelin restaurant, so it's in the typical range of similarly rated establishments. Frankly, however, this was a better meal than two-Michelin places we've been to on out previous trip two months ago, so from that perspective we considered it to be, maybe not a bargain, but completely worth it.

review_data.review_title: Top flight Korean with that Michelin flair
review_data.review: The food was phenomenal, and the service was excellent. Some of the descriptions of the food, spices, and inspirations for the dishes were a little unfamiliar coming from a Korean influence, but the food definitely gives a sense of place. Each dish was flawless, although the Mackerel dish was a little too fishy for our taste. (Our mistake for never having had Mackerel before.) The Octopus was delicious; tender and perfect. review_data.review_title: Bargain café at Petticoat Lane Market
review_data.review: There’s nothing to beat a good old-fashioned Full English Breakfast. Here at Café Nora (formerly Café Thyme), there are nine fry-ups to choose from, ranging from £6.95 to £7.95, all cooked to order and served with tea or freshly ground coffee and toast or bread. The English Breakfast of two eggs, two rashers of bacon, sausage, hash browns, baked beans, mushroom, black pudding and grilled tomatoes is a firm favourite. There’s also a Mediterranean Set Breakfast and Vegan Brunch with vegan sausage and avocado. For the more adventurous, there is Eggs Benedict, omelettes, pastas, salads, pancakes, burgers, panini, jacket potatoes, sandwiches and filled baguettes. Something for everyone. Situated in East London’s popular Petticoat Lane Market, on Wentworth Street and near the corner of Middlesex Street, the café is run by Turkish chef Ebru Puleri and her female Turkish friends. It’s a friendly, warm place, with comfortable seating, and popular with local workers, neighbours, market traders, students and visitors to London. It is walking distance from Aldgate East Tube and Liverpool Street Station. Open daily from early morning to 3pm.

It was about $230 for 3 courses and wine but we left feeling like it was certainly worth it A nice restaurant for a special occasion and my wife loved the veal Marsala. Make sure you have a limoncello with dessert.

In Paris, the competition in the fine dining category is fierce.  It’s as if every night is a playoff game and everyone is gunning for the title. Here, a Michelin Star might actually be worth more than in other cities. And if you’re lucky enough to be on vacation, with back-to-back dinners at this level, you would imagine that someone has to lose. It was with this pressure we dined at Pur, having just experienced newly starred Saturne the night before.  Would there be space for its unique take on starred excellence?  Pur is a classic fine dining experience. This is not a let down. Imagine the finest ingredients in unique combinations. Now imagine them served at a level that take six dishes and create wonderful arc.  While identifying individual dishes is useless as Chef Aie Okabayashi is sure to adjust the menu based on what’s seasonal, the one prevailing taste we encountered was “smoke”. Similar to the essence of barbecue, there were hits of smoke and wood in unexpected delicate places like fish. Yes there was a duck course that was one of the best…the skin by alone could have been a delicacy.  Lest we forget, two of the six courses were desserts, with a palate cleanser that could be a dish in itself. Actually, the that cleaner tart “soufflé” was probably our favorite, and the pastry chef, who busily prepped dishes all night next to our chef’s table, humbly admitted it was his as well.  We opted not to commit to the wine pairings, but the Sancerre and Margeux by the glass were excellent. If you prefer cocktails, their take on the Moscow Mule is worth the price. And don’t be intimidated by the six-courses. It’s the right size and takes about three hours, so it was well-paced.  Finally, the service was superb. It doesn’t hurt that we were seated at the chef’s table with a window into the kitchen where Chef was making sure no detail was overlooked. And yes she made one trainee remake a simple amuse-bouche simply because he failed to sprinkle the dust in the right direction. And an anniversary cake for a couple celebrating theirs was reset because it sat a few minutes too long.  Situated in the sexy Park Hyatt Vendome, this is far more than a “hotel” restaurant. It’s epic…they brought their A-game on an average Tuesday evening. But hey, this is Paris, and the next Michelin wannabe is right around the corner!  The good news is that Pur has the goods, elegance and fine creations, to keep that star shining.

review_data.review_title: Fantastic experience that should be on your list when you visit Queenstown!
review_data.review: My wife and I were lucky enough to first experience The Bunker on a trip to Queenstown back in 2002. We were quite surprised that after such a long time the restaurant was still making memories for locals and tourists alike.  This is not a restaurant that you decide to drop in on at the last minute. It's often booked out well in advance and sports around 7 or so tables for a very intimate dining experience with friends or loved ones. In fact, we booked over a month in advance to make sure they could seat our party of 5.  Plan to take your time and this is one location that it pays to trust the kitchen, as they have a fantastic degustation menu, featuring ingredients from the South Island of New Zealand. Matching New Zealand wines are also on offer and in my opinion you're missing a fabulous experience if you choose to à la carte.  We started the evening with cocktails followed by a dish titled "Amuse" - described as a daily creation or local delicacy. On this day, we were served a starter of Cervena Venison. It came cooked perfectly with 3 beautiful contrasting sauces.  The next dish was a choice from the Southern Ocean or Marlborough region, scallops or wild boar respectively. I chose the boar - Mille Peuille of apple, parsnip remoulade with a well matched Amisfield Pinot Gris from Central Otago.  The next course hailed from the West Coast or Bannockburn - Conit of baby abalone, or Seared Loin of hare and braised leg. The hare was served with confit kumura (New Zealand native sweet potato), sour cherries, kawakawa jus and a Surveyor Thompson Pinot Noir from Central Otago.  A nice little citrus sorbet followed as a palate cleanser.  The Main course was either a Centrol Otago Alpine Merino lamb backstrap and braised neck, or Nelson sourced seared pink snapper. The Merino Lamb was spectacular, served with baby vegetables, pea sponge, thyme jus and a Church Road Reserve Merlot/Cabernet blend from the Hawkes Bay.  Dessert was a classic New Zealand kiwi fruit pavola with local fruit and mascarpone with a Brancott Letter Series Late Harvest Sauvignon Blanc from Marlborough.  Lastly, we were treated to a local cheese selection with figs, nuts and a Cloudy Bay Late Harvest Riesling from Marlborough once again.  The wait staff were fantastic. Every course was described in detail and the quality of service was second to none.  Treat yourself to an experience and make sure The Bunker is on your list when you next visit Queenstown.  Highly Recommended.

On arrival the small (but cosy) place was very busy and having no booking we were offered a seat at the bar.This offer was accepted and the owner came straight over with the drinks menu , we are not knowledgeable about Portuguese wine so asked for some guidance. We quaffed the lovely wine ordered some more and asked for the food menu. The owner who was clearly in control of the whole show was exhilarating to watch , moving from table to table , laughing and joking with the customers and even playing the accordion from time to time a delight to observe. The food arrived Covert ( bread with oil ) the Prawns in garlic sauce and a portion of Bacalhau a bras (codfish , slices of potato and egg cooked in the oven) both dishes were absolutely delicious. Unfortunately by siting at the bar the Toucinho do Ceo do Avo ( Grandpa`s Heavenly Tart ) was positioned on the bar top just in front of us , so a portion along with a very nice glass of port had to be consumed to finish the night. Everything about the place is fantastic, the food is amazing , the staff are friendly and great , the atmosphere is homely , all in all a great find , needless to say we only managed the one bar that night best laid plans and all that. Grau Douro thankyou for a Fantastic Evening. We will be back.

However Garden Mezze felt like a bit more of 'an occasion' compared to some of the other tourist focused places in the area. It is probably a little more expensive than some others - but not by a great degree and the setting, atmosphere, service, and food meant we didn't mind.

user_data.user_tags: Foodie;Urban Explorer;Like a Local;Peace and Quiet Seeker

review_data.review_title: Very nice Thai food within the hotel
review_data.review: We were staying at the Anantara Layan Phuket Resort and was highly recommended this Thai fine dining restaurant by the hotel staff. Was a buggy ride away from the hotel room.  The view from the restaurant was great. Good before the sunset so that you can enjoy both the sunset and the night view.  Alfresco dining is recommended because you will have the unblocked view to the sea and the pool. But get ready your insect repellent and embrace the heat because the fans weren't helping much.  We ordered a set menu for 2 pax. Was decent but nothing exceptional. The pace of serving was a little too lengthy, we actually got bored waiting for food after a while. We got seated by 6 pm and we left the restaurant at 8.30 pm.  Would I recommend this to anyone? If you are staying at the resort, why not because you don't have much choices there.  If you are making a trip here from elsewhere, I don't think you miss much.

review_data.review_title: A must go if you are staying in the Hotel
review_data.review: It was late when we checked into the Hotel so we decided to roam around the hotel and find food. We came to this Sea.Fire.Salt Seafood restaurant and decided we just eat here, that was the best decision the day.  We were impressed with how elaborated the Salt can be with every dish during our dinner. The staff appeared to know their Salts very well too. The recommended type of Salt for us tasted just great with our food.  We had a table indoor because it was raining. Ambiance was great. Food was great.  Service was prompt and attentive.

review_data.review_title: Great food in a beautiful setting
review_data.review: We shred beef Lok Lok, eggplant salad with sesame, Char koheung - fish dish and a beer to wash it down. Service was Ok but the restaurant was slammed with way to many large groups.

user_data.user_tags: Art and Architecture Lover;Foodie;Urban Explorer;Like a Local

review_data.review: We had an absolutely amazing experience sharing Argentine wine, traditional asada, and stories with people from around the globe during our night with Steaks by Luis. The event runs three times a week in a space that is typically reserved for a wine club. Although our group had about 20 people in it, it served to be a very intimate experience. The night began with a toast and traditional appetizers while mingling with other guests and staff. We continued by a nice presentation of the food and an introduction to the evening by the staff. Next, we sat down for a wonderful dinner - each part of which was superb. My boyfriend's favorite part of the evening was being able to head outside on the balcony with Luis, who showed him grilling techniques and talked about his experience with gastronomy. The food, wine, and company were all wonderful, and we loved being able to meet people during such an enjoyable experience - we have even kept in contact with a few! The staff was absolutely fantastic. Luis was happy to share his knowledge, Pierre was knowledgable and very interesting to talk with, and the rest of the staff was superb as well. A definite highlight of our trip!

Was looking for a nice spot for a beer after arriving in BA and down the street from the hotel a bit, we found Sullivan’s. Stopped in for a local beer and enjoyed the setting so much we decided to have dinner here. The menu is smallish but the food was good and reasonably priced. We had a bottle of Argentinian white wine form north of the country and it was very good.All in all a great spot if you live in the Palermo district.

Excellent food cooked by Theo and his amazing staff. This really is a gem in Park Lane, and superb value for money if you choose the regional tasting menu. It really is a culinary experience visiting the restaurant, with a wonderful vibe and ambience. Theo is such a personable and all round nice guy. Always welcoming to guests visiting the kitchen.  Cannot wait to return next year, thanks to all

review_data.review_title: Amazing night, fabulous food, superb experience
review_data.review: 2020 has been a terrible year for most, but we had a particular hard time with loss of both my parents so close together, so planning a day in London like we had was a welcome relief. It was my daughter's 21st birthday celebrations, and I have always wanted to go to Theo's restaurant as I am a huge fan of his and Saturday Kitchen on BBC1 so always enjoy his appearances on the show. The restaurant knew it was my daughters birthday as I had informed them, but we were not expecting the fuss that was made of us. We were put on one of the chef's tables (Matt Tebutt and his wife had the other which just made my night) and Theo greeted us, wished Lily a happy birthday. He had time for everyone in the restaurant, guests were in and out of the kitchen all evening. The waitress we had was just fabulous and we had an absolutely superb evening, one we will be talking about for years to come. We had the Sicily taster menu, 5 courses with wines that accompany the courses. every course was sublime. And at £50 a head, thoroughly affordable for the West End of London. Cannot wait to return, already planning my next visit. And I know I keep thanking him, but thank you Theo, and thank you to all the staff. You really have a great team

A magnificent steak collection with info on how to order. Waiters dont always speak english. The steak was superb and well cooked. The condiments were out of this world as was the free salad. Desserts were massive

This is Thai food restaurant attached to the beach. The atmosphere is very good. Taste is great.  Signature cocktail is strange but it's tasty. This is combination between Thai food and drink. Don't miss it.  Staff is very kind and helpful.  In my opinion, Takieng restaurant should get Michelin star...
Met with colleagues for dinner. The staff was incredible, the food was amazing and the wine selection/pairing was spot on on. They set aside a great wine for us. We had a great time!

review_data.review_title: Best Indian Food in Siem Reap
review_data.review: Mr. Narain is a wonderful host. Vastly experienced in the hospitality business, his restaurant is easily the best in Cambodia for Indian food. A great eclectic menu to satisfy all tastes, I seriously recommend this restaurant to anyone who likes quality with a great ambience.

We came across this cosy cafe restaurant and decided to give it a try... Very friendly welcome from the team. Comfortable seating. Good selection of dishes from snack size sharma kebabs to tagines. All well presented. Everyone enjoyed the food. Ours was the sharma.. One of each.. A chicken and a meat... Served with fries on the side. We were given a taster of lentils and olives.. Which were delicious. We enjoyed our visit. THANK YOU Shokran

review_data.review: I would say that this score is exactly what I feel about experience in this restaurant. 5 courses served at very fast pace. Sea scalop dish come on time from the kitchen but served bit late, hence temperature was not good, it would be much better that it was served on time. Knife for meat dish was with wooden handle which is against HACCP standard. One of the service personnel had scent of cigarettes on his fingers (must say this was noticed when bill was presented, not during food service) All the rest was very good and food was really tasty. Reception was very professional, very good and clean rest room facility. Price wise this was on high end side. Still, I recommend this place.

review_data.review_title: Rightfully one of the best Paris restaurant
review_data.review: Room is not clogged with tables, you will have your personal space. We visited Boutary for lunch and it was an excellent experience. (Check pics AngeloB971), buttersquash soup with lobster ravioli, caviar from their own Bulgarian farm, wild seabass, roasted duck leg with black garlic (in house made), desserts 2 to choose from; tangerine or chocolate, either way you can not miss. Very plesant and professional staff, moderate prices. Worth to visit while in Paris, dinner time reservation is a must.

review_data.review_title: Did not live up to the reviews
review_data.review: We chose this restaurant because it seemed well reviewed. There were 3 of us and we all thought the food average, service was average and event the wine was average. Maybe we caught them on an off night but it shows that not everybody has the same experience.

user_data.user_tags: History Buff;60+ Traveler;Peace and Quiet Seeker

review_data.review: Wow last night was worth recording now, not waiting till we are home. This was no ordinary experience as this was in a private home with a maximum of 10 guests from anywhere in the world. It turned out that there were only 4 of us last night and all English speaking so it was great. Dan and Henry made us very welcome in their home with a lovely cocktail to start. I could go on but i want to talk about the food. Dan serves 5 courses all paired with different wines. The food was amazing, i don't eat raw fish but last night i could have licked my plate and asked for more. Absolutely delicious. As was the Brussel sprout bisque, again something else i wouldn't eat at home. Griddled white asparagus next with amazing homemade XO sauce. Onto main of Ribeye beef with Peruvian yellow chili sauce and finished off with pear and burnt butter brownie. This meal was truly amazing, everthing beautifully presented,portions are not tiny, glad of the walk back to our apartment. Thanks Dan and Henry for a great night.

Much like its sister restaurant around the corner, this place is also an authentic Sicilian restaurant. A bit bigger than its sister but still crowded with a happy atmosphere. A loud music played in the background and everybody are happy. The food is fresh and tasteful and prices are very reasonable. Service was excellent. As pescatarians, we had many food choices. A vegetarian can also find starters and mains he or she can have. Great place, highly recommended.

We booed after reading the good reviews on TripAdvisor. We weren’t disappointed. The place is a bit old fashioned. The main place is not too big but it has additional space at the back and maybe upstairs. The gentleman who served us was very kind. He spoke with us from time to time and made us feel welcome. We took the tasting menu, which was excellent. We needed some adjustments with the food, which wasn’t a problem. The food and deserts were delicious. Together with a very nice bottle of Burgundy, we paid 240 Euros for two people. We will return!

My husband and I were there last year (2014) in December during the week. It was wonderful : a quite romantic evening with excellent service and delicious food. However we went there last Friday Dec 4th and it was a mad house : had to wait in the small bar area even tho we had reservations, the noise so loud none of us could hear? The duck was the best ever!! and they offered after dinner drinks to accommodate Just be sure to go on a week night
Amazing experience, food was outstanding and service top quality for Queenstown. We had Shane serving us who was extremely knowledgeable and made us feel so welcoming for such a big group
We were a party of 6 staying at the Lotus Blanc. Great service, fantastic food. A must do, a treat!!

Very quiet evening when we visited - just one guy serving but it seemed like many people were getting takeout. Calm, relaxing atmosphere and food was good (just not as excellent as expected given high reviews.) Really good value for money.

review_data.review: This was the best dinner we had in Prague! Even though the place is small it manages to be cosy and relaxed rather than cramped. The wine & food were amazing - following the recommendations of staff we found several wines we absolutely loved. Service was friendly. Really recommend booking here if you visit Prague.

We stumbled upon a wine dinner the evening we visited Sea. Fire. Salt. and had a lovely meal in a lovely setting. The service was quite good, timing good as well and the food was very nice. The restaurant prides itself on the different types of salts it uses and they even have a lovely guy named Ton who is the salt sommelier. The prices aren't cheap, but they are in range with the other resorts and restaurants in the area. Would recommend for a nice meal out.
Cool little restaurant with amazing burgers! If you are visiting Marrakesh don’t miss this place, it absolutely deserves its no.1 spot on Tripadvisor 👍

review_data.review_title: Such a lovely addition to the Prague restaurant scene
review_data.review: We visited this brand new restaurant after we had heard some positive signals from friends.  I remember this restaurant used to be "U Cervena Tabulka", and it is amazing what they have done with the place, you will not recognise it. They have a beautiful bar area, and an incredible wine selection/cellar.  The food was simply out of this world. We all tried different dishes, which were all amazing. Our favourites were the octopus carpaccio, the lamb and definitely the cherry dessert.  Will be back soon!

Came here with an old work colleague for lunch on a Wednesday. We arrived at 12:15 and there was no wait and plenty of tables. It became very crowded by 12:45. The buffet had a nice variety of food, lots of hot dishes with written explanations of the content which was very helpful.  Buffet style is nice so you can try a little of everything and go back for your favorite items.

review_data.review: Amazing little place well worth seeking out. Beautifully tasty food and exceptionally good value. The pastilla was great but the falafels were even better and the Moroccan cakes for dessert were divine. Three "mains", two desserts, two sodas and a big bottle of water all for about £15 before tip.  I think we may need to try it again before we leave.....

review_data.review_title: Top little spot just off Jemaa el Fna
review_data.review: A wonderful little family restaurant set just off Jemaa El Fna. Head up the road between Cafe de France and La Marrakchi and there it is on the right.  I had some beef briouates the the chicken tanjia, my wife had the Moroccan salad and then a mixed grill all of which were fabulous and tasty. We finished with Moroccan cakes and mint tea, the latter of which was the best mint tea of our tour so far.  If you want some great Moroccan food slightly away from the noisiest that Jemaa el Fna has to offer, give this place a try.
Delicious food and great service. Really appreciated the recommendations. Recommend the bun cha Hà Nội which was delicious!

user_data.user_tags: Foodie;Urban Explorer;Shopping Fanatic;Peace and Quiet Seeker

review_data.review: Great restaurant with lots of character. Loved the way the cocktails were presented, plus they were delicious. Food was piping hot and fresh. Excellent all round!

Picked this place on our first night in Siem Reap based on the excellent TA Reviews - they are spot on! Service and food both delightful!  They picked us up and dropped us off for free from our hotel (we tipped the Tuk Tuk driver though)  The dining room looks as good as the photos and staff are all lovely - smiling and attentive.  Cocktails at $3.25 was too good to miss!  Nice little Spring Roll amuse bouche.  Starters of Fried Noodles and Vegetable Fritters we’re fresh and flavoursome. (6 large fritters)  Mains of Vegetarian Curry and Pan Grilled Beef Steak Lok Lak Style - both delicious!  Lovely home made ice cream and coffee to finish. ($36 + Tip)

We had a memorable dinner at this place. We didn't try the 6-courses set menu because the hostess informed us that it's likely too big for us, so we ordered different starters and main dishes according to her recommendation. They were very helpful in letting us shared the plates. We'll definitely come back to this place.

review_data.review_title: Very good eating place in Hotel Le Bristol
review_data.review: It's our first dinner in Paris this trip. The place was almost full on both levels. We ate in the lower level where the open kitchen situated. All dishes ordered were impeccably prepared. However, they were too salty and the veal was too cooked to our medium rare order.

review_data.review_title: A beautiful place, great service and delicious food
review_data.review: We had Lunch at Calden del Soho and loved it. The interior is beautiful, the staff was very friendly and attentive. Provoleta was delicous and the steak and salad were perfect. The best place we had lunch this time being in Buenos Aires as all the other restaurants we went to felt touristy, overpriced and were lacking service. We would highly recommend Calden del Soho.

review_data.review: I don't care who the chef is, or at least whose name is over the door, you simply never ever get any sense of passion, love or caring in the cooking of the food in an inernational hotel. When will we ever learn. This is a restaurant for those with a bucket list to tick off not a true love of food. It was nice enough but formulaic and 'mass produced'. God, the chefs must get bored of cooking Theos 'famous' dishes. We were guests of some friends so just let the evening unfold without any fuss but let me tell you, by the time the waiting staff have finished enthusing about their favourite dishes (the ones they have been told to push) there may as well not be a menu. The pace at which the waitrons poured the relatively expensive wine was outrageous. This was not great service this was rushed. Finally the restaurant is nondescript in the extreme, basically in the basement, and could be anywhere in the world.

review_data.review: Me and my boyfriend visited Utsav last night for our last night in New York and it was great. The food was very reasonably priced and the staff were friendly. It had a really chilled and laid back atmosphere which was a really nice contrast to the normal hustle and bustle of Times Square.

One of our favorite places in New York. Always delicious. Always busy. Always friendly. this night was great as usual. The Gamberi Caprese - very interesting. Bucatini Cachio Pepe - sublime. Spaghetti Neri Lobster - a feast for the palate and the eyes. The Verdure Grigliate and Patae Limone rounded out the fare. looking forward to out next adventure at Piccola Cucina.

review_data.review: This was a return visit and the anticipation was well-deserved. Every dish was a gastronomic experience to cherish. The Duetto Sandwich is hard to share but worth every morsel. Ravioli Funghi Salsiccia to die for. Cacio Pepe is a traditional Appulian dish done perfectly. Pachheri Seafood excellent. Patate Limoni and Verdure Grigliate great accompaniments. It is very noisy, but mostly from people talking and having a good time. Spontaneous dancing broke during our meal - just like dining in a local resto in southern Italy.
What a great surprise! French restaurant operated by French people. Great service and wonderful food!!!

review_data.review: Simply amazing menu choices - super fresh, healthy, wholesome, delicious and great customer service. Whoo Hoo I highly recommend this restaurant

This is another amazing social profit enterprise. They take in disadvantaged youth. They train, educate, coach and mentor young adults to be self-sustaining and employed in today’s world. They also run a 1st class restaurant with excellent food, ambience and incredible customer service. Thank You for what you do.

They take in disadvantaged youth - train them in life skills, work skills, hospitality management - being servers, cooks , chefs , managers etc. Then trainees are sent out to other hotels for internships and then after graduation they all find jobs in the local Siem Reap hospitality industry. A remarkable process. Train your staff well and they will look after your customers.

This restaurant is a dream and a Haven for dis-advantaged youth. Paul and his wife ( owners) started this project in order to provide youth with an opportunity to acquire life, work and employment skills. Youth go through an internship process for a number of months. When they graduate they are hired at local high-end restaurants as they have excellent hospitality skills, knowledge abilities. So, when in Siem Reap you will have to eat , so I ask that you dine at this restaurant support their cause.

I found this restaurant on TA / the reviews are very good and decided to try one of it’s Khmer stir fry dishes the menu is varied and has Khmer, Thai and some western food choices as well. The chicken stir fry was excellent - lots of fresh veggies and lots of really nice breast of chicken. The sauce was great, thanks - will be back again .

we always stop in and have dinner or lunch @ Tevy’s Place. Tevy and her staff are so welcoming. Excellent service and menu choices at a very reasonable price. She brings in and trains young women in all aspects of running a restaurant. Thanks for being a successful entrepreneur and for training, coaching and mentoring young adults.

I love this restaurant. The food was s 12/10 , interesting ambience, great staff and excellent customer service . If you sit a front you can watch them cook your meal. All female staff. This place is another social profit enterprise. Tevy supports educational programs for disadvantaged youth - specifically females in Siem Reap. She deserves the Order of Cambodia. Pucs to follow

simply an amazing restaurant. Here is another example of a social profit agency that works the restaurant business and puts $$$ back into the community. You just have to go there. The food, music, decor, ambience and customer service is Outstanding.

As I said it was Ok, not Oh Woo Hoo amazing like the other reviewed. Now that being said It was mid afternoon and I stopped for chicken satay as an appies and had a glass of red vine. The server showed me the bottle and I reviewed the label as I held the bottle. What I was served was a cold glass of wine. It either not what he showed me or an opened bottle that was in The fridge. Somewhat disappointing. The satay presentation was good - but the chicken was chewy and lacked a proper seasoning. The service was very good.

Just love this place..only downside is that it is now so popular you have to book several days in advance, especially for Thurs, Friday and Saturday nights. We just don’t want it to change. The owner is so grounded I hope that won’t be the case and he deserves every success. We visited yet again last Friday and tried the new £20 buffet menu. The tofish we usually love wasn’t available but the owner gave us the most delicious plate of noodles to compensate. The new dishes of guacamole, gazpachio, cashew ‘cheese’ and mung beans did not disappoint. In fact I think this was the best meal we’ve ever had there. Warm welcomes, lovely service, superb food with sublime flavours... but sssssh... don’t want anyone else to discover it!!!! Sadly, too late!!!

We went at lunch, experience is amazing. Very small and imtimate, tables are on top of each other, but that adds to the experience. Lunch is an incredible value, most of full menu options available for only $11, wow. The Sicilian Meatballs are amazing. Staff is all Sicilian, feel like you are there as they are all speaking native. If you want amazing hand made pasta, do go here, do not even think about showing up without a reservation. If you are looking for a quiet, say romantic setting this is not it. However the intimacy adds to the experience.

This is an outstanding restaurant. I understand the high ratings over the years. The work coming from the kitchen are masterpieces. Chef does an amazing job of bringing flavors together. He is big on adding an orange tint to items, very different! They did nice presentation for my wife's birthday, this is appreciative. Also the service is outstanding, nothing spared yet is not over the top. Would highly recommend this establishment. Also $70 for 3 courses of this quality is very good compared to some other similar offerings in the city.

review_data.review_title: Amazing Contemporary Korean Tasting Menu worth the price..
review_data.review: I visited Jungsik with my son to celebrate his birthday and it was the right choice. We had an amazing dinner that we will remember for a long time worthy to be celected for an important event.  We went with the tasting menu. I have to mention that the menu is quite rich and many dishes so go hungary since you should not miss any part of it.  The menu starts with amuse bouche with 5-6 items each very tasty giving you a good sense of what to come. It is then followed by fried oysters, octopus and crispy red snapper, then a Korean soup Songee followed by a wonderful Wagyu Tanderloin then a pallette cleanser sorbet then deserts ...  The atmosphere is very pristine, cleanly decorated and very kind and knowledgable service who explain the subtleties of each dish.  It is quite expensive but worth it since it is an experience you will never forget ..
Amazing food, beautiful dining area. We decided to have an Italian meal and could not have loved it more.
It was a very nice family experience. Great food and service. Prem was our chef and John was a waiter. Both did great. We highly recommend it

It is licensed so you could order alcohol here. It is also air conditioned which was wonderful and a bit more expensive. I would return.

review_data.review: Our party of four had a takeaway dinner one night from this business. After ringing to place our order, we were able to pick it up almost immediately. The slow cooked meat melted in your mouth and the potatoes were delicious. Maybe a little more potato is warranted for four people. We thought that, last time we were in Queenstown a few years ago. We did order a salad to go with it and although tasty, was nothing like the salad in the photos online. We would use this venue again. Not a large menu, but a tasty one.

We visited on Valentine’s Day after I had previously been 2 year ago. A booking is recommended. Thoroughly delicious! The place is not what you would think from the outside and is very small and intimate. The guys who run it are great fun and very welcoming. The food was amazing and the atmosphere perfect. I would highly recommend anyone to visit and can’t wait to visit again!!

We came to the Be Bop Lobby Bar on a family's recommendation and now we are also recommending it to everyone.  This is a large, light and airy bar in the lobby of the Radisson Blu Hotel. The staff are extremely knowledgeable and very friendly.  They have any drink you could want from wines to cocktails and spirits but they also have a special cocktail menu which runs along the theme of 'be something' ie be an alchemist, be offline, be a Chef, be Woody etc. These cocktails all come with props and some of them are very theatrical but great fun.  We tried quite a few of the cocktails off this menu because it was so good that we visited twice whilst on our trip to Prague. All the staff were really friendly and we got chatting to Jan at the bar on both visits, what a star he is.  My best tips are sit at the bar if you can, order off of the "Be" cocktail menu, get involved and have some fun. We are back to Prague this October and will definitely be back in here.

We came here on friday night around 6.45 was a little busy. We ordered spicy potataoes was soft and not too overpowering. Falafels were nice and big with tahini sauce i enjoyed it Chicken shawarma was slightly undercooked came with rice salad and bread. Service was friendly the owner/staff welcomed us and greeted us with salam the islamic way.

The sommelier talked about each wine in detail - and he did know his wines. The food was exquisite. The service a little patchy but maybe because we had a trainee waitress.

review_data.review_title: Raise a Glass to the Rajdoot!
review_data.review: We enjoyed our final meal of the holiday here at Rajdoot and were a little apprehensive as all meals so far over the weekend had been very good. I suppose we were just thinking that law of averages would mean at least one poor meal? How wrong we were as we enjoyed probably the best evening of our family break. From the moment we exited the taxi outside the staff were out to greet us, very friendly and made us all feel welcome. You can tell that they all care about their business as they couldn’t do enough for us and even offered us complimentary drinks at the end of the meal. There were all the traditional offerings and some nice specialities too. We had Jalfrezi , chicken saag, and a king prawn korma and I liked the option to have your chicken grilled / tandoori as a opposed to plain. Of course we had poppodums and chutney to start, who doesn’t? All washed down with ice cold Cobra beer. I think everyone was slightly jealous of my wife’s Chicken Saag, not only was it delicious but it came in the hit sizzling pot, which I always feels adds to the experience and I’d encourage them to serve the jalfrezi this way! I’m not sure if this is practical but it certainly makes the table go “ooooh” as the sizzling dish approaches. I also liked the fact that when I asked fir my naan bread well done it came nice and crispy just as ordered. Seating was covid friendly and waiters wore face masks so no issues with hygiene/ CV19 To finish off our fabulous evening the waiter allowed my son in law to take away his beautiful cobra glass that he’d been eyeing all evening, which I felt was a lovely touch and made Toms night! Thanks to all the staff at the Rajdoot and I would encourage you to try this place whilst in London. Highly recommended

We’ve eaten at benihanas many times before in various locations and ALWAYS given it a 5* review but this time it barely rated 1* and so I thought that you should know  We booked for 1pm and arranged to meet our son and his wife. We weren’t allowed to sit and enjoy a drink however as we were rushed off to our table with a warning about how soon we would have to vacate the table. Not exactly welcoming  Eventually a waitress came and took a drinks order and gave us menus.  Long wait then she came and took our orders and a while later we finally got a drink. In the us where they live on tips this would never have happened  The chef was Spanish and very difficult to understand. In fact the other three in my party had to ask me what he was saying.  The display was almost non existent. Other benihanas have always put on a real show with food being flicked around, a few ingredients and utensils in the air etc  As for the food each part of the food was served individually so apart from the soup it was all pretty cold  A few selected comments  The fish was tasteless The chicken was dry The prawns were tasteless The rice was tasteless. The foie gras is highly recommended, ir was served on a slice of blueberry bread and was delicious. Very friendly staff, which enhanced the experience. Will visit this restaurant again. Highly recommended if you want a good meal at a reasonable price.

review_data.review_title: Quality Italian food at this prestigious venue
review_data.review: It is many years since our last visit to Theo Randall - the place has been brightened up considerably since our last visit and although the low ceiling will always remain it is not so noiticeable.  The restaurant features a regional menu which at £50 including wine is excellent value for money - tonight's was from Emilia Romagna but our prefernce was from the wider A la Carte which is priced by the dish.  Starters of Minestrone and a Cheese souffle were both filling and delicious and mains of Pappardelle and Sea Bream very enjoyable. We finished with a shared Italian cheese course followed by a lovely soft chocolate cake.  The wine list is a lovely tour of Italian regions but there is a nice choice of wines by the glass enabling us to try a selection, the Jermann Pinot Grigio and Planeta Chardonnay both superb examples.  Service was friendly and efficient and we were much more impressed than on our previous visit.

We found this place by chance, loved it. The staff were really friendly and had a laugh with us. The place is stunning and the food was outstanding. Set menu/price, very good value. Before you get your starter you get 19 little Morrocan starters, beautifully done. Very relaxing. Would recommend. I had the sea bass which was beautiful.

This was my first visit to Devran after an Arsenal game. My friend was a cop in the local station so he knew the place well. The place was packed with Turks. Very few Brits. I ordered the mixed grill. The portions were massive. We struggled to finish the food. The room right at the back has 6 or 7 tables. Service is iffy here but the food more than compensates for the bad service. We ordered turkish tea at the end. It took more than 3 reminders and in excess of 30 mins to get the tea. I would recommend you get a table in the main seating area.

review_data.review: We found this small and unassuming little restaurant near our hotel, based on other reviews. I must say it did not disappoint. Can definitely recommend the creamy prawn curry as well as the chicken with mint. The waiter, Anil, was very charming and happy to make recommendations. I'm sure we'll be back. Thanks so much!

review_data.review_title: Elegant, clean with good service. The food was not up to these standards.
review_data.review: We found Gazebo via Google's listings and it had good reviews. Everyone else inside the restaurant was Indian/Asian. We had very high expectations. The place was beautiful and every detail was looked after in an excellent manner. If you take friends, clients or a date, they will like the ambiance. Parking was a little tough but that's a Dubai issue.  Finally comes the food. It was a mixed bag. The appetizers were above average. The Beryani was pretty good. The rest of the food was average and the Hamour fish was below average. I grew up in Dubai and have had Indian food in many cities around the world. The food here is nothing special. Very unfortunate as it was one of very few restaurants we were able to try during our trip to Dubai and we didn't expect a well appointed restaurant with Indian food in competitive Dubai to have average food.  You can get an idea of pricing from the attached image. The prices, for an American consumer, were very reasonable. Total for 4 people was around $70 (255 AED).

review_data.review_title: Decent pub food, make sure to check the receipt
review_data.review: Been here 3 times in our stay and pub food was consistently good. Recommend for a change in scenery from the resort. Pains me to say there seems to be an “honest mistake” scheme running with happy hour. The invoice each time is brought over and they quickly show your free drinks but the total you pay also includes the free. If you question it they then remove the “free ones” . Every time same problem. When pointed out the 3rd time the waitress got passive aggressive and began being super assertive. It is a classic ruse to gain funds. Don’t begrudge them in this time however check your bill if you care about your happy hour drinks :). Would I go back - sure. Would I trust the bill - no way

The pasta options were all delicious. We tried the Wild Boar, Eggplant and a Seafood pasta and all were very good. The Chicken Milanese with fingerling potatoes was also very good capped off with one tiramisu. All in all a good family Italian night and reasonably priced for NYC.

We arrived in happy hour and had a few drinks before ordering food. The menu was very good and I opted for prawns. Very good. We were going to stay longer but the music was turned too loud for us. We have since had a very sincere apology from the owner, apparently it was a new member of staff and I am assured it won’t happen again. I would certainly return and recommend this bar.

This place smells so good as you walk by, that you just have to stop and have a bite. The restaurant is really, really small, seriously. If you have a part of 5 or more, like I did, be ready to wait for an hour or more, especially at dinner time. So keep that in mind. What I saw was a lot of take outs, which is something that I will do next time, instead of dining in and waiting forever. They just don't have the space, and they don't take reservations or call aheads. Other than that, the staff and hostess were great and friendly. The pizza is done right inside brick oven. I believe one pizza would feed two, but if you're really hungry, then just stick with one all for yourself. The price is decent, compared to other NYC restaurants.

review_data.review_title: Terrible experience with very ordinary food
review_data.review: We dined here for the Christmas eve lunch event which was quite a costly experience, even for Argentinian standards. The food was inedible in parts and acceptable canteen style food at best which just didn't match the arrogant and often unfriendly wait staff. Besides one very charming, eager young waiter who was happily training his English while working on our Spanish at the same time, there were quite a few older "supervisor" type staff members around who mostly did nothing but chit chatting to each other. The meal had wine included and we had even double confirmed in writing that indeed all wine is included but alas, in the end one of these supervisors had nothing else to do but tell us upon leaving that "only half a bottle per person was included and you drank two bottles in total". Then he pretended to be super generous by telling us "But that's okay, for you I will take it off the bill" clearly fishing for big fat tip. Well- not for that "my friend", we left without tipping a single cent on purpose while we had originally intended to leave some money. All in all, extremely disappointing experience.

Outstanding meal. We were there for a belated Valentine’s Day meal and absolutely loved the experience. Mitra was warm, friendly and professional and the food was nothing short of amazing. We had the Momo as a starter which tasted fabulous and I also enjoyed the Paneer Tikki as a main course. Will certainly be returning for other celebrations.

review_data.review_title: The best pool and bar at the hotel.
review_data.review: Had incredible service from the team here, especially Lert who is just the kindest and loveliest person.

review_data.review_title: A place to come back to
review_data.review: A great place for modern Cambodian cuisine. We enjoyed their 6-course tasting menu which we were told changes frequently. Staff were friendly and professional matching the nicely designed place.  Starters were a traditional Cambodian mango sallad with the twist of dried snake. This was followed by a deep fried pork stuffed sticky rice cake served with a fish ceviche dip. Both dishes were traditional yet modern. Precise and fresh flavours.  Main course comprised three dishes: lemon grass spiced fish with a tofu-ginger sauce, a papaya-basil-shrimp soup and curry-peanut fried beef tenderloin. All stretched the flavours in their own way. Together they formed a united, well composed dish.  It all finished with a raspberry sorbet, a sticky rice and sesame seed roll and coconut sago soup. Balanced and tasty.  Only drawback is the lack of a wine pairing meny. So we grabbed all their eight wine-by-the-glass and enjoyed our wine pairing ourselves.  If you are looking for a modern khmer restaurant in a modern and comfortable atmosphere, pick Kroya.

review_data.review: This restaurant is a little bit hidden gem because of its location, but it is definitely worth of visit. The staff was friendly and attentive and the food was very tasty.

We were in this elegant and trendy restaurant for lunch and it was very nice experience. Everything was perfect. Wonderful ambience, creative menu, very friendly staff and tasty food. We will definitely come back!

review_data.review_title: Such a lovely Sunday experience! Brilliant taste and even nicer service 😊
review_data.review: Such a lovely Sunday experience! Brilliant taste and even nicer service  We stumbled across here as our last brunch before heading home. It’s a good location close to the airport but good parking outside too. The owner is so so friendly and welcoming and accommodative. We initially nearly didn’t go because I don’t eat egg but he mentioned they make vegan crepes too with buckwheat! Music to my ears… I had the veggie burrata, sundries tomato savoury crepe and my partner had the chicken crepe & a Nutella crepe. Must add the sweet potato fries which we had on recommendation are a must! Thank you for a fabulous brunch!

We visited this place during our stay in Prague as it was close to our hotel and because of good reviews. The experience was excellent. Food was really very good and the staff were excellent. Highly recommend anyone anyone who visits Prague goes to this please for a and ambience.

We decided to eat here after reading the reviews and it is in the next hotel along. I am so glad we did! We both said that it was the best meal we had eaten on the island.  We sat inside and all the staff were very attentive. I had a mocktail called Anantara which was lovely and my boyfriend had a glass of the Thai Shiraz which was actually good quality.  We didn't have starters but both had sea bass, mine on the rock plate and partners steamed. We were given 3 different salts to have with it which were explained and all went very well!  We had dessert too which was the best sticky rice and mango I've had on the island and we had the banana in coconut which was amazing.  The staff were lovely and the food fabulous. If you are in the Mao khao area it is definitely worth a visit, it's not the cheapest but it is worth the extra money!

review_data.review_title: Great food and super friendly service
review_data.review: We dined here everyday during our 4 day trip to Siem Reap. The food is delicious, the staff are really friendly and the manager always stops by for a chat which makes us feel so welcome. We have had the fish amok, beef salad, fresh vegetable rolls, beef lok lak, prawn salad, etc. and everything has been beautifully prepared. We spend about USD12 for the both of us each time with beers - this is really great value. Glad we found this place on day 1 :)

We came here for lunch on our first day and were a little underwhelmed given the great reviews on Tripadvisor. I had the fish amok which was very salty and my husband had the fresh vegetable rolls which were not very tasty. The meal cost us USD15 altogether with beers which isn’t a lot but you get much better quality food / value at Tevy’s.

I ate here and liked it so much that had to come again in a few days - and I was NOT even staying at the hotel.  Location and views are beautiful!  Food is delicious. Staff is super great and helpful. Hasan Bey, the manager, is just awesome! And the head chef comes out at least once during the dinner and has a chat with you. And his attire - well kept, ironed, clean. You KNOW the person respects his job.  Everything is great! From salads, to kebabs, to pilafs (PLOV). Anyone in Istanbul - I would definitely recommend visiting.

A fabulous lunch experience. We enjoyed the 6 course lunch tasting menu which is highly recommended. We chose not to do the wine pairing though and didn’t have the optional cheese course, but there was more than enough food.Service was very good from the welcome at the front door to when we left. Service is included and if you’re choosing not to have the wine paring, there’s a great wine list. We will definitely be going back.

We had steak and fish on 2 different nights, and both nights were amazing. The staff arranged for items off menu that really surprised us in a good way, and the hightlight was the steak - done just right - medium - with really good char on the outside, but still juicy on the inside. They also have an awesome kids menu, which truly made for a good experience for me since we have a young child with us.

We had already been to quite many good places during our city break in Paris but Au P'tit Curieux turned out to be the crown jewel of this trip. Food just perfect (we had 3 courses of classical French cuisine); great wines that were recommended with expertise by the host; cosy, easy-going ambience. But the best of all: What a devoted and personal service. So glad we found this restaurant. We were really happy after this dinner!

Nicely decorated restaurant with very friendly staff. The menu is small and offers only fresh ingredients, related to the season. Starters, pasta and desserts that all sounds delicious, at affordable prices. We had poulpe and arancini, gnocchi and ravioli accompanied by some good wine and we loved it. Make sure to reserve a table. We will definitely come back.

review_data.review: Ate here as part of my G Adventure tour in Cambodia. Food was good. The area is economically depressed however this place offers hope. It's good to give back.

review_data.review_title: Delicious and relaxing first meal in Siem Reap. Thank you, Darin!
review_data.review: Our midnight flight to Siem Reap was delayed by bad weather and we didn’t arrive until 6 am. Exhausted from lack of sleep and a short air journey made long by 3 hrs at the airport + 4 hrs of flying, we did our best to salvage our first day with a visit to the National Museum and lunch at Kroya. I emailed the restaurant and requested a table in the air conditioned dining area. Mr. Darin Eang promptly replied to my email and arranged for a quiet table. Service was excellent and the food was delicious. Three diners chose to share Kroya’s version of local Angkor dishes while our 2 gentlemen opted for hamburgers. Our driver Mr. Lim Pengkhun commented that the Fish Amok tasted very authentic. We also loved the raw beef salad.  Thank you again, Darin and restaurant team!

My wife and I first visited Pepe Nero in 2015 and we were back, this time with friends, to celebrate yet another wedding anniversary.  One of the charms of this restaurant is its location, around a 10 minute walk from the main square through some interesting back streets (mind the speeding mopeds). The restaurant send great directions but if you're a little nervous about finding Pepe Nero they will send someone out to the square to collect you.  The food was delicious and the service was perfect. We chose from both the Moroccan and Italian menus and our friends agreed this was a real gem of a place. Great atmosphere, food and service and the prices are amazing.  So glad we came back and having informed the restaurant at the time of booking that it was our anniversary they supplied a lovely complimentary cake at the end of our meal.  I cannot speak highly enough of this establishment - top class
